data.name: rndAccuracyToggle.ToolTip
data.value:
Normalizes spell accuracy values to 100. All spells will pass the initial accuracy check, but offensive spells can still miss since they always roll a comparative-Agility hit rate calculation after the base chance.
Status spells: Changes positive/negative status effects' accuracy to 100. All spells: Changes all spells' accuracy to 100 (Also includes Escape, Extinction, etc.)

data.name: rndZoomToggle.ToolTip
data.value: Changes maximum zoom distance from 2-12 [1 is default]. Value is NOT a multiple, this is just a range of stable values available. Higher values may cause instability, especially on hardware, due to increasing the visible amount of content.

data.name: expFilenameLabel.ToolTip
data.value:
Output filename. If nothing is entered, defaults are: <input filename> for Z64 files and "merrowpatch" for IPS patches. Save location is the "Patches" subfolder in the same folder as the Merrow executable.
Z64 Export will not overwrite your original Z64 file, it will instead export a Z64 copy into the save location. However, exports will automatically overwrite any existing file with the same name already in the save location. It will also create a 'filename + Spoiler.txt' file in the same directory that lists patch contents, seed, and other information.

data.name: newLabel.Text
data.value:
● IMPORTANT CHANGE TO LOST KEYS LOGIC: There's a new Progression option that's enabled by default: 'Put Book in Fire Region.' If this is enabled, the Book region will now overlap the Fire region in the same way that Wind and Water do: the Book can now be in any Fire location in addition to the Book locations (but Fire is unchanged.) We found that the Eletale Book wasn't really adding anything to routing. Between it being stuck in the endgame, and the relative size and wing density of the Fire Region, the late-game dungeons were rarely visited and getting to Brannoch was extremely straightforward (and therefore, so was getting the Book.) This new option can be disabled to return to the Fire/Book distribution.
● Fixed a massive error with IPS patch data handling, that caused any patch that changed Brian's clothing colours to be unusable.
● Fixed a couple MERROW UI enable/disable-state errors, which were locking some checkboxes on open (i.e., locked until another option was enabled and then disabled again).

data.name: rndShortcodeLabel.ToolTip
data.value:
A shortcode that contains the currently-enabled randomizer settings. Editing this code will change all the settings at once. Codes are tied to version numbers, because the number of Merrow options changes from version to version.
Error-checking isn't perfect yet, so invalid codes should just blank themselves. They may crash.

data.name: rndShuffleShannonToggle.ToolTip
data.value: Shuffle/randomization will exclude the final two Shannons entirely, so the Eletale Book and the Dark Gaol Key will be in their original locations. If this option is *not* enabled, softlock protection will still prevent either item from being carried by either Shannon; they will always be found earlier.

data.name: rndChestToggle.ToolTip
data.value:
Change the contents of all chests. [WARNING - Including gems or wings can cause sequence breaks.]
When LOST KEYS is enabled, this determines what fills in the *rest* of the chests that aren't taken up by the 5 Key Items (gems and book) and Wings.
SHUFFLED: All default chest contents are shuffled among all chests. STANDARD: Chests are randomized to contain any standard item. STANDARD&WINGS: Chests are randomized to contain any standard item or wing. STANDARD&GEMS: Chests are randomized to contain any standard item or Elemental Gem. CHAOS: Chests are randomized to contain any standard item, wing, or Elemental Gem. WINGS: Chests are randomized to contain any wing. GEMS: Chests are randomized to contain any Elemental Gem. WINGS&GEMS: Chests are randomized to contain any wing or Elemental Gem. CUSTOM: Chests are randomized as selected below.

data.name: rndDropsToggle.ToolTip
data.value:
Change the items dropped by non-Boss enemies. [WARNING - Including gems or wings can cause sequence breaks.]
All options other than SHUFFLED do not give enemies 'No Item'.
SHUFFLED: All default item drops are shuffled among all enemies, including blanks. STANDARD: Drops are randomized to contain any standard item. STANDARD&WINGS: Drops are randomized to contain any standard item or wing. STANDARD&GEMS: Drops are randomized to contain any standard item or Elemental Gem. CHAOS: Drops are randomized to contain any standard item, wing, or Elemental Gem. WINGS: Drops are randomized to contain any wing. GEMS: Drops are randomized to contain any Elemental Gem. WINGS&GEMS: Drops are randomized to contain any wing or Elemental Gem. CUSTOM: Drops are randomized as selected below.

data.name: rndGiftersToggle.ToolTip
data.value:
Shuffle/randomize the items granted by item-gifting NPCs. [WARNING - Including gems or wings can cause sequence breaks.]
When LOST KEYS is enabled, this determines what fills in the *rest* of the gifters that aren't taken up by one of the 5 Key Items (gems and book.)
Shannons and their endgame items (Eletale Book and Dark Gaol Key) are included by default, but softlock protection will guarantee that they will be granted by earlier gifters. Optionally, use the toggle below to exclude Shannons: they will carry their items as default.
SHUFFLED: All default gift items are shuffled among all gift NPCs. STANDARD: Gifts are randomized to be any standard item. STANDARD&WINGS: Gifts are randomized to be any standard item or wing. STANDARD&GEMS: Gifts are randomized to be any standard item or Elemental Gem. CHAOS: Gifts are randomized to be any standard item, wing, or Elemental Gem. WINGS: Gifts are randomized to be any wing. GEMS: Gifts are randomized to be any Elemental Gem. WINGS&GEMS: Gifts are randomized to be any wing or Elemental Gem. CUSTOM: Gifts are randomized as set in the below menu.

data.name: rndWingsmithsToggle.ToolTip
data.value:
Change the items granted by Wingsmith NPCs. [WARNING - Any of these options may cause sequence breaks, or remove Wings entirely.]
SHUFFLED: All wings are shuffled among all wingsmith NPCs. STANDARD: Wingsmith items are randomized to be any standard item. STANDARD&WINGS: Wingsmith items are randomized to be any standard item or wing. STANDARD&GEMS: Wingsmith items are randomized to be any standard item or Elemental Gem. CHAOS: Wingsmith items are randomized to be any standard item, wing, or Elemental Gem. WINGS: Wingsmith items are randomized to be any wing. GEMS: Wingsmith items are randomized to be any Elemental Gem. WINGS&GEMS: Wingsmith items are randomized to be any wing or Elemental Gem. CUSTOM: Wingsmith items are randomized as set in the below menu.

data.name: rndSpellOverridesToggle.ToolTip
data.value: Checks special override data to certain shuffled spell combinations. If available, fixes will be added that allow volatile combos to work, and/or improve visuals on combos with effect/scaling issues.

data.name: rndSpellItemsToggle.ToolTip
data.value: REQUIRES Spell Shuffle to be enabled to have an effect. Update the names and descriptions of spell items. Name is determined by the modifier spell's element, and the description is based on the modifier's effect.

data.name: rndSpellRebalanceToggle.ToolTip
data.value: Adjusts damage values for most spells. Makes many assorted spells more useful, slightly nerfs the most powerful spells. Also causes most multi-level spells to scale inversely: the more precise low-level spells will do slightly more damage per hit than the high-level bigger ones with more hits.

data.name: rndDistributeSpellsToggle.ToolTip
data.value: Distributes the four most powerful combat spells (Avalanche, Magic Barrier, Water Pillar Lv3, Large Cutter) so that each is sorted into a different element when shuffled. Also generally tends towards the spells being at the higher end of their respective elements, to allow for better race enviroments.

data.name: rndElement99Toggle.ToolTip
data.value: Element level maximum is increased from 50 to 99. No new magic will be acquired past Level 50, but spell and melee power will continue to increase. [WARNING: If you raise your elements to exactly 50-50-50-50, you will no longer be able to gain xp or pick up world spirits, due to a code restriction. Until it can be removed, avoid 50-50-50-50.]

data.name: rndSoulToggle.ToolTip
data.value: All spells have a chance to trigger the Soul Search effect on hit, revealing enemy details. Also replaces the vanilla Soul Search 'magnifying glass' icon with a more compact one, since you'll be seeing it a lot. [NOTE: Every time the Soul Search effect occurs, to you or an enemy, Brian will gain an additional MP EXP, due to the way the spell effect is coded. This will cause you to gain MP quicker.]

data.name: rndSpellToggle.ToolTip
data.value: Change the properties of all spells as discrete units, except for unlock level and menu positioning. SHUFFLED: Redistribute spell properties randomly, with some crash protection rules. <SPELL>: Set all spells to use the specified spell's properties. No crash protection.

data.name: rndSpellNamesToggle.ToolTip
data.value: Spell names are updated to be a prefix/suffix combination based on the original and modifier spell. Ambiguous: Hinted spell names will randomly select whether original or modifier provide prefix or suffix. Obvious: Hinted spell names will always be in the format (original prefix, modifier suffix).

data.name: rndFrenchVanillaToggle.ToolTip
data.value:
FRENCH VANILLA is a set of Quality-of-Life options for improving the vanilla game experience, without changing it too much. Intended for all experience levels. It is compatible with LOST KEYS (and recommended, honestly.)
Enabling FRENCH VANILLA will overwrite many MERROW settings to create an improved ruleset. Disabling FRENCH VANILLA will simply disable many of the options enabled, rather than setting them back to whatever setting you had them set to previously. Be sure to re-check any options you want after disabling FRENCH VANILLA.

data.name: rndLostKeysToggle.ToolTip
data.value:
LOST KEYS is a special ruleset based around the Elemental Gems and Wings only appearing *once* each, scattered around the world, allowing for original pathing, experimental routing, and risky choices.
Enabling LOST KEYS will overwrite many MERROW randomizer settings to create a playable ruleset. Disabling LOST KEYS will simply disable many of the options enabled, rather than setting them back to whatever setting you had them set to previously. Be sure to re-check any options you want after disabling LOST KEYS.
LOST KEYS Regions: - Earth: Melrode Monastery to Solvaring (& Yellow Wings) - Wind: Dondoran Treasury to Zelse (& Blue/Green Wings) - Water: Dondoran Treasury to Nepty - Fire: Limelin to Brannoch (& Red/Ivory/Black Wings) - Book: Brannoch Castle (not including Beigis)
PROGRESSIVE: Search each region, and gamble on when to move on. Each Key Item (gems/book) and Wing is available in its 'region' (so, anywhere up to the point where vanilla progression requires it.) It will either be held by a chest, a gifter, or the boss. Wingsmiths are not randomized by default. Black Wings appear in Fire region (Limelin/Dindom/Brannoch), along with new 'Ivory Wings'. Ivory Wings replace White Wings, and teleport to Shamwood. Lavaar is considered the Ivory Wingsmith. Fire Ruby is REQUIRED to enter Brannoch Castle. Crystal valley warp enabled. Shamwood exit shortcut enabled. Spell and boss shuffle are enabled, but can be disabled if desired. Some randomizations and options cannot be disabled.
OPEN WORLD: Search each region, and rush the endgame as soon as you feel brave enough. ALL progression locks (doors, shortcuts, boats, secrets) are unlocked, except for final Shannons. Each Key Item (gems/book) is available in a random Lost Keys region (like PROGRESSIVE, but with key items shuffled between the default region slots.) All four Elemental Gems are required to traverse Brannoch Castle roof to reach Mammon's World, which still requires the Book to enter. One of each wing is scattered among ALL possible Key Item locations, including Ivory Wings. Crystal valley warp enabled (and unlocked). Shamwood exit shortcut enabled. Spell and boss shuffle are enabled, but can be disabled if desired. Some randomizations and options cannot be disabled.

data.name: rndBossOrderToggle.ToolTip
data.value: Randomize the order of all bosses other than Beigis and Mammon. Boss stats will maintain their stat:BST ratios, but BST will be scaled to the level of the boss they're replacing, and they will drop the appropriate progression items.

data.name: rndMonsterExpToggle.ToolTip
data.value: REQUIRES randomized/scaled stats or Boss Order to be enabled to have an effect. Uses an approximate formula based on enemy Base Stat Total (BST) to recalculate experience gained on victory. Useful for making more significantly scaled/randomized runs theoretically possible.

data.name: rndMonsterScaleToggle.ToolTip
data.value:
Scales enemy stats by simple multiplication. Has a more severe effect than variance.
NOTE: The 'Enemy stat scaling' feature is applied AFTER the effects of 'Randomize monster stats'. Setting both to higher values may cause extreme results.

data.name: rndMonsterStatsToggle.ToolTip
data.value:
Randomizes enemy stats. All monsters in each region will receive new stats, randomly chosen from a range from lowest to highest local vanilla values for that stat. Increasing the Variance modifier will increase the width of that range, beyond the vanilla lowest-highest bounds. Bosses are included in stat randomization, but their Variance scaling is halved to make up for their generally larger numbers skewing output.
Example: At Variance 1.0, all Holy Plain enemies will get a new random HP value between 9HP (Were Hare HP) and 28HP (Big Mouth HP).
NOTE: The 'Enemy stat scaling' feature is applied AFTER randomization and Variance. Setting both values higher may have extreme results.

data.name: rndFireBookToggle.ToolTip
data.value:
If this option is enabled, the Book region will now overlap the Fire region, in the same way that Wind and Water overlap. The Book could now be found in any Fire location in addition to the Book locations (but Fire distribution is unchanged.)
Enabled by default for LOST KEYS, can be disabled to return to old behaviour (Fire and Book areas are separate.) Requires LOST KEYS to be enabled.

data.name: rndIvoryWingsToggle.ToolTip
data.value: Replaces the White Wings with Ivory Wings, which warp the player to Shamwood. The Melrode Wingsmith will not grant an item, and instead Lavaar in Shamwood will grant the Ivory Wings upon interacting. SHUFFLED Wingsmiths treat Lavaar as the granter of the Ivory Wings and shuffle accordingly.

data.name: rndUnlockDoorsToggle.ToolTip
data.value: Unlocks all progression-related locks. Gems, Book, and Key are no longer required to progress. This includes doors, boats, shortcuts, and portals, and also unlocks the Crystal Valley Postern, if enabled.

data.name: rndCloakPaletteToggle.ToolTip
data.value: Changes the colour palette of Brian's cloak. RANDOM: Generate a palette at random by hue-shifting the original palette randomly by 0-359 degrees. Has a 50-50 chance to be a light/dark palette. CUSTOM: Edit the hue-shift value as desired below.

data.name: rndStaffPaletteToggle.ToolTip
data.value: Changes the colour palette of Brian's staff. RANDOM: Generate a palette at random by hue-shifting the original palette randomly by 0-359 degrees. Has a 50-50 chance to be a light/dark palette. CUSTOM: Edit the hue-shift value as desired below.

data.name: rndTextPaletteToggle.ToolTip
data.value: Changes the text colour palette. RANDOM: Generate a palette at random by hue-shifting the original palette randomly by 0-359 degrees. Has a 50-50 chance to be a light/dark palette. CUSTOM: Edit the hue-shift and light/dark values below. SHUFFLED: Select one of the below four included colours at random. <COLOUR>: Use one of four default included colours.

data.name: rndTextViewToggle.ToolTip
data.value: If enabled, the text colour palette will be displayed to the right for reference, so you can ensure it's acceptable. If CUSTOM is selected, you can manually set a hue offset value from 0-359, and click the circle to change between light/dark palettes.

data.name: crcHelpLabel.ToolTip
data.value:
This is a CRC (N64 file checksum) Repair Tool. The checksum is a value calculated based on a certain portion of a Z64 file, that is used to verify that the file is legitimate. Making modifications (with tools or patches) to that portion of the file will cause the checksum to be incorrect, which causes certain hardware and emulation to fail on boot.
This tool can be used to recalculate and update the checksum of a Z64 file, allowing hardware to recognize it as legitimate without errors or issues.
It uses a DLL compiled from existing checksum calculation code in C. Full details of the algorithm and the license information for the C script are available in the repo, under the CRC64 subfolder.
This tool is restricted to Z64 files, to prevent possible memory errors and other problems, but it is experimental software. Please ensure you back up any files before attempting any checksum repairs. It is your responsibility to know what you are doing to files, and why. Merrow is offered without warranty: please refer to the license readme file for more info.

data.name: expModePatchIPS.ToolTip
data.value: For experienced users only. GENERATE FILE will create an IPS binary patch file with the chosen settings. If certain options are selected, the patched rom will need to be repaired with the CHECKSUM REPAIR TOOL below.

data.name: advHelpLabel.ToolTip
data.value:
This is a generic IPS patch generator. Handy for quick hacks and tests, it will generate a clean IPS patch for whatever use you may need. Enter the PATCH CONTENT you want to write (in hexadecimal 2-character bytes), and the ADDRESS to start writing at (as a 6-character hex string).
Always make backups of your files before patching. This tool will generate properly formatted patches, but it is your responsibility to know what you are patching and why. Merrow is offered without warranty: please refer to the license readme file for more info.

data.name: binHelpLabel.ToolTip
data.value:
This is a binary file data extractor. Handy for quick reference and grabbing bulk info, it will read the input file at specified locations and fetch the specified values, and optionally, create a text file containing the read bytes in hexadecimal format.
Populate the EXTRACTION LIST with as many entries as needed, in comma-separated hexadecimal or decimal strings in the following format: (Byte_Address,Byte_Length) with no brackets and another comma before the next entry. Ensure you specify whether all addresses/lengths are written as hexadecimal or decimal, using the lower left options. If you would like the exported data to be output to file, check the box at the bottom.
This tool can currently only access values in the following ranges: Address: 000000-FFFFFF (DEC: 0-16777215) Length: 0000-FFFF (DEC: 0-65535) If the ranges are too restrictive for your uses, please get in touch. This is a first attempt but it can be adjusted in future versions.
This tool is as restrictive as possible, to prevent possible memory errors and other problems, but it is experimental software. It is your responsibility to know what you are reading from files, and why. Merrow is offered without warranty: please refer to the license readme file for more info.

data.name: binExtractLabel.ToolTip
data.value: Enter comma-separated hexadecimal or decimal values in this field. Each entry should follow this format: (address),(length),... The binary file will be read starting at [address], for [length] bytes. After entry, ensure you select below what format each value type is in.

data.name: hlpHelpText.Text
data.value:
1. WARNING Merrow is considered experimental/educational software, and is offered without warranty or liability. By using Merrow, the user agrees to full responsibility for the results of using Merrow. Back up files before patching. Merrow (as it is currently maintained by Hangedman Design) contains no networking or analytics functions, and all best faith attempts are made to ensure it has no bugs or issues that would compromise either the users' computer, or their game hardware. This is not a guarantee, and this also may not apply to alternate forks of Merrow's code or any derivative works.
2. WHAT IS MERROW? Merrow is primarily a "randomizer" for the game "Quest 64": a tool for shuffling around various game elements of the NA/U Z64 version of Quest 64, offering many randomization, difficulty modification, and quality-of-life options. The goal of a randomizer is to breathe some new life into an old game for existing fans by remixing it on every playthrough. Merrow also aims to add improvements for new players, to make the game easier to get into. Merrow is also a collection of hex data collation and patching tools.
3. HOW TO USE MERROW The basic workflow is: select the features/randomizations/options you'd like to use, go to the last tab of the Randomizer section, select a clean file and export the patched version. Features in Merrow all have tooltips with more detail, available by mousing over a function's name. To see a list of all functions in brief, visit https://hangedman.itch.io/merrow.
4. HOW TO GET STARTED QUICKLY Double-check https://hangedman.itch.io/merrow to ensure you have the latest version, and follow these steps: A. Open Merrow, and select "Quest 64 Randomizer" from the "Quest Features" menu. B. Want a better vanilla game, or to add quality-of-life fixes to your randomizer? Enable "FRENCH VANILLA". C. Want to play the recommended randomizer ruleset? Enable "LOST KEYS". D. Optionally, enable any other features you want. E. Switch to the "FILE EXPORT/CHECKSUM" tab. F. Click the big "SELECT Z64 FILE TO PATCH" button, and select a clean Z64 Quest file. G. Enter a filename if you want, and click "GENERATE FILE". The Patches folder will automatically open, with your patched file and spoiler log (if enabled).
5. WHAT IS LOST KEYS? In brief, enabling LOST KEYS distributes a single copy of each key progression item randomly throughout each world region, with logic to prevent the game from being impossible. This allows for varied and unique paths through the game. It also enables a set of other options designed for varied play, such as Shuffled Spells. If you're playing LOST KEYS and you want a quick overview of the changes, take a quick look over the Lost Keys Guide PDF, included with the Merrow download.
6. CHANGELOG A complete changelog is available at the bottom of the Itch page, at https://hangedman.itch.io/merrow.
7. LICENSE and COPYRIGHT For development purposes, Merrow is copyright of Hangedman Design. But Merrow is MIT-licensed, functionally open source with conditions. License details are available at https://github.com/hangedmandesign/merrow. Development assistance is welcome. An overview of the Merrow codebase and code structure is available at https://github.com/hangedmandesign/merrow. Merrow contains no game code or copyrighted assets. Item sprites, names, etc, are used within Fair Use constraints. Rights to "Quest 64" and all associated materials are maintained by the copyright holders and Hangedman Design makes no claim to them.
8. FEEDBACK If you have feedback or issues, your best bet is to comment on the itch page. Submitting your spoiler log (with version, shortcode, and info) makes solving bugs much easier. Feel free to suggest feature ideas, but please understand that we have considered many features in the past, and there may be good reasons why we didn't add something. We are necessarily limited by the pre-play-patching method we use and by the data we have access to, and that's why this is not a major hack, omnibus mod, or total overhaul. I can also be reached on Twitter at @JonahD but I can't guarantee a timely reply, especially if I've moved onto other projects.
